WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.200
So, this example has some serious effects for production-sized apps where you have authentication

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:21.879
or things that testing should not be confirming. One of the difficulties when doing production-sized

00:00:21.879 --> 00:00:27.520
apps and you're running it through unit tests is interacting with outside sources. This

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:32.340
can be authentication, this can be database requests. One of the things that we recommend

00:00:32.340 --> 00:00:41.080
you do is you listen to a flag or a global option of shiny.testmode. If shiny.testmode

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:48.080
is true, I recommend having a different UI or server or reactive behavior given this

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:56.700
flag. You can have things like the authentication isn't even addressed. If I do a restricted

00:00:56.700 --> 00:01:02.380
database call, maybe instead I load a CSV of information. One, we're not testing the

00:01:02.380 --> 00:01:06.139
database, we're actually just testing the shiny app, so we need to try to isolate our

00:01:06.139 --> 00:01:13.139
tests to what we can control. Using this flag, we can turn that behavior on or turn it off.

00:01:13.139 --> 00:01:20.980
I think it's just really great as to how you can override your app's default behavior.

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:24.980
Let's look at the app that we've been doing in the past two videos where we ask our name

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:32.419
and it'll tell us the first letter of our name. Then let's just add in a third field

00:01:32.419 --> 00:01:39.019
of penguins. To lighten the mood a little bit, we're going to say, how many penguins

00:01:39.019 --> 00:01:46.059
are going to be coming for dinner? Let's just add this into our app. We have it here. I'm

00:01:46.059 --> 00:01:51.500
just going to run it for demonstration purposes. I click greet. It says, hello, first letter

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:59.940
of your name is B, and there are 333 penguins coming for dinner. This is fun, but if I keep

00:01:59.940 --> 00:02:05.099
hitting greet, if we look as to where this penguin count is coming from, it's coming

00:02:05.099 --> 00:02:10.100
from this authenticated database request or something that I'm going to have return random

00:02:10.100 --> 00:02:19.779
data. If I click greet again, that's 330, 324, 336. This is not deterministic at all.

00:02:19.779 --> 00:02:23.699
This is therefore not useful for testing because if you keep running this test over

00:02:23.699 --> 00:02:28.699
and over, it will fail. There will be no way for it to be correct because the data changes

00:02:28.699 --> 00:02:39.100
underneath. Instead, we can listen to our flag. I'm going to just wrap this one part

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:48.179
and say, if we'll get an option of shiny.testMode, and if we'll default this value to false,

00:02:48.179 --> 00:02:55.580
but if it's true, then I want to return a test database request. This is something that

00:02:55.580 --> 00:03:02.899
returns static data and will only retrieve what I want it to have. Otherwise, if I'm

00:03:02.899 --> 00:03:09.580
not in test mode, then let's just do the authenticated database request. This will be stored into

00:03:09.580 --> 00:03:15.199
penguin data, and then the penguin data will count the number of rows, and then hopefully

00:03:15.199 --> 00:03:21.639
we have a consistent count. Now, if I just run my app in reload app, this is not in testing

00:03:21.639 --> 00:03:26.679
mode, so we should still see our original behavior. I see Barrett. We see greet. It's

00:03:26.679 --> 00:03:35.479
something like 333, 321, a different amount of each time when I click greet. Let's run

00:03:35.479 --> 00:03:44.320
this just kind of looking at our application here. If I run this with the app, and I call

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:52.880
app$view so that I have it, it opens up in the Chromium-based browser, and I have what's

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:58.960
your name. We call set input Barrett. We call app greet. We can see that it updated, and

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:03.279
here it says, hello, Barrett. First letter name is B, and there are 68 penguins coming

00:04:03.279 --> 00:04:09.880
for dinner. It's a funny phrase, but it's 68. It's not 300, and so if I click greet

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:15.800
again and again and again and again, 68 is now constant, and it's still going to stay

00:04:15.800 --> 00:04:25.859
there. If I look at the values to see what we have, app$get values, I have output penguins.

00:04:25.859 --> 00:04:31.239
There are 38 penguins coming for dinner. I could actually update that so that we have

00:04:31.239 --> 00:04:38.920
another exported test value of the penguin count. If I update with the penguin count,

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:48.200
say penguin count equals a reactive expression where I export that penguin count, save it,

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:53.640
and then I have to, I'm going to stop this app here, and then I'm just going to restart

00:04:53.640 --> 00:05:03.799
those interactive tests where I run app, and I click greet, and let's view it. I don't

00:05:03.799 --> 00:05:07.559
need to necessarily open up the viewer at the beginning. It's usually useful when debugging

00:05:07.559 --> 00:05:21.040
errors, but it still says 68. App$get value of export equals penguin count is 68. Perfect.

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:26.160
Now we can make assertions on this value, and it'll be consistent every single time.

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:30.679
This is just so useful for getting around those database calls that take five, 10 minutes

00:05:30.679 --> 00:05:36.359
to execute, or you're asking a different API about something that is outside the control

00:05:36.359 --> 00:05:41.880
of Shiny. We want these unit tests to be consistent and fast. That way you want to do them, and

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:48.880
you want to do them often.

